==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*mari'', from Indo-European ''*mori-'' ‘sea’.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[meri]] (Dutch [[meer]]), Old High German [[meri]] (German [[Meer]]), Old Norse [[marr]] (Swedish [[mar]]).  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[mare]], Old Irish ''muir'' (Breton [[mor]]), Old Church Slavonic [[море]] (Russian [[море]]), Lithuanian [[mare|mãre]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'mere/

===Noun===
'''mere''' ''m'' (''pl'' '''meras''')
# the [[sea]], [[ocean]]
# a [[lake]] or body of water

